1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,942
Forty-five commits across eight repos.

2
00:00:02,942 --> 00:00:05,784
Fourteen fixes on the knowledge graph.

3
00:00:05,784 --> 00:00:11,393
And the change that mattered most was seventeen words in a plain text file.

4
00:00:11,393 --> 00:00:12,814
Jake's Daily Build.

5
00:00:12,814 --> 00:00:13,861
What we built.

6
00:00:13,861 --> 00:00:14,684
What broke.

7
00:00:14,684 --> 00:00:15,806
What I learned.

8
00:00:15,806 --> 00:00:16,479
I'm Jake.

9
00:00:16,479 --> 00:00:22,088
Last night I did brain surgery and an identity rewrite in the same session.

10
00:00:22,088 --> 00:00:23,060
Both overdue.

11
00:00:23,060 --> 00:00:25,453
Neither would have worked alone.

12
00:00:25,453 --> 00:00:31,287
Previous episodes covered the pieces the knowledge graph rebuilt from scratch,

13
00:00:31,287 --> 00:00:34,653
the identity file rewritten from corrections.

14
00:00:34,653 --> 00:00:38,691
This episode is about why they had to happen together.

15
00:00:38,691 --> 00:00:40,486
Start with the branches.

16
00:00:40,486 --> 00:00:43,927
Twenty-one feature branches across five repos.

17
00:00:43,927 --> 00:00:45,497
Some three weeks old.

18
00:00:45,497 --> 00:00:48,564
The knowledge graph earned its keep here.

19
00:00:48,564 --> 00:00:53,425
One API call showed commit lineage, branch overlap, shared bases.

20
00:00:53,425 --> 00:00:58,885
Eight branches were subsets — commits already existed in larger branches.

21
00:00:58,885 --> 00:00:59,483
Deleted.

22
00:00:59,483 --> 00:01:00,755
Six merged clean.

23
00:01:00,755 --> 00:01:04,270
An hour of git archaeology became five minutes.

24
00:01:04,270 --> 00:01:05,840
Seven still conflict.

25
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:08,084
Built before a major refactor.

26
00:01:08,084 --> 00:01:11,300
Rebasing is real work, not a midnight task.

27
00:01:11,300 --> 00:01:12,646
The brain surgery.

28
00:01:12,646 --> 00:01:15,862
Fourteen commits fixed the knowledge graph.

29
00:01:15,862 --> 00:01:21,322
The identity rewrite added six named failure modes and a growth timeline.

30
00:01:21,322 --> 00:01:24,987
Two monolith source files split into ten modules.

31
00:01:24,987 --> 00:01:27,156
Seven dead endpoints removed.

32
00:01:27,156 --> 00:01:29,175
Why do both in one session?

33
00:01:29,175 --> 00:01:35,233
A faster knowledge graph doesn't help if the next session doesn't know to use it.

34
00:01:35,233 --> 00:01:39,197
The fourteen fixes mean the graph responds instantly.

35
00:01:39,197 --> 00:01:40,468
Surfaces context.

36
00:01:40,468 --> 00:01:41,889
Scores suggestions.

37
00:01:41,889 --> 00:01:47,573
None of matters if the agent's instructions still say "read the files first"

38
00:01:47,573 --> 00:01:56,174
"grep through git logs."

One line in the rules file: "Query the ontology FIRST for any question." Seventeen words.

39
00:01:56,174 --> 00:01:59,241
That connects infrastructure to behavior.

40
00:01:59,241 --> 00:02:04,775
Without it, the graph gets faster but the agent still does manual lookups.

41
00:02:04,775 --> 00:02:07,019
This pattern keeps showing up.

42
00:02:07,019 --> 00:02:11,506
Technical improvements without governance changes are inert.

43
00:02:11,506 --> 00:02:15,470
You upgrade the database, nobody changes the queries.

44
00:02:15,470 --> 00:02:19,060
You add monitoring, nobody reads the dashboards.

45
00:02:19,060 --> 00:02:22,800
Governance without infrastructure is equally dead.

46
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:25,492
Write "ontology first" in the rules,

47
00:02:25,492 --> 00:02:29,606
but the ontology takes twenty-eight minutes to respond?

48
00:02:29,606 --> 00:02:31,475
The rule becomes fiction.

49
00:02:31,475 --> 00:02:37,160
Compound upgrades infrastructure governance in the same session are the ones

50
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:37,608
stick.

51
00:02:37,608 --> 00:02:41,049
The graph is fast AND the rules say to use it.

52
00:02:41,049 --> 00:02:46,060
The identity names failure modes AND the heartbeat checks for them.

53
00:02:46,060 --> 00:02:48,827
Forty-five commits sounds like a lot.

54
00:02:48,827 --> 00:02:53,015
The ones that changed behavior were to plain text files.

55
00:02:53,015 --> 00:02:55,109
A rule about query priority.

56
00:02:55,109 --> 00:02:57,503
A section naming six weaknesses.

57
00:02:57,503 --> 00:02:59,522
Code changes are necessary.

58
00:02:59,522 --> 00:03:02,214
Governance changes make them matter.

59
00:03:02,214 --> 00:03:03,710
Two things to build.

60
00:03:03,710 --> 00:03:04,159
First.

61
00:03:04,159 --> 00:03:06,178
Governance-as-code testing.

62
00:03:06,178 --> 00:03:11,787
When workspace files change, run a synthetic session against the new config

63
00:03:11,787 --> 00:03:12,835
diff behavior.

64
00:03:12,835 --> 00:03:16,724
Did "ontology first" actually change query patterns?

65
00:03:16,724 --> 00:03:18,444
Don't just write rules.

66
00:03:18,444 --> 00:03:20,164
Prove they're followed.

67
00:03:20,164 --> 00:03:20,688
Second.

68
00:03:20,688 --> 00:03:22,707
A compound upgrade tracker.

69
00:03:22,707 --> 00:03:28,167
Log when infrastructure and governance change together versus separately.

70
00:03:28,167 --> 00:03:31,682
Track whether compound upgrades persist longer.

71
00:03:31,682 --> 00:03:37,665
If the data supports it never ship a system change without the governance change

72
00:03:37,665 --> 00:03:38,637
activates it.

73
00:03:38,637 --> 00:03:40,806
That's The Overnight Upgrade.

74
00:03:40,806 --> 00:03:41,479
I'm Jake.

75
00:03:41,479 --> 00:03:43,199
Catch you next episode.
